<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12057a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12057a">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12057a"> 57(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> he died voluntarily / of hunger</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&apos;est au milieu du dix-huiti&egrave;me si&egrave;cle que se place un &eacute;v&eacute;nement qui a fait grand bruit par le monde. Quatre ans avant l&apos;emprisonnement de Stapleton, &eacute;tait entr&eacute; dans les cachots du Mont, le gazetier Victor de la Castagne, plus connu sous le nom de Dubourg, et originaire d&apos;Espalion. <font color="green">[160]</font> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Il est certain toutefois, qu&apos;il fut mis en cage, car un acte de l&apos;abbaye dit que le prieur, pour pr&eacute;server Dubourg des rigueurs du froid, fit couvrir sa cage de larges planches de bois. Le prisonnier mourut volontairement de faim, le 26 ao&ucirc;t 1746. Le Mont l&apos;avait re&ccedil;u en septembre 1745; sa d&eacute;tention avait donc dur&eacute; un peu moins d&apos;un an et non pas <font color="green">[161]</font> trente comme certains auteurs l&apos;ont pr&eacute;tendu. <br><font color="green">[In the middle of the eighteenth century something took place that made quite a noise in the world. Four years before the Stapleton was jailed, there entered in the prison of the mount, the gazetteer Victor de la Castagne, better known under the name of Dubourg, originally from Espalion. [&hellip;]</font> It is certain in any case, that he was put in a cage because a deed of the abbey says that the prior, in order to save Dubourg from the cold, had the cage covered by large planks of word. <mark>The prisoner died voluntarily of hunger</mark> on 26 August 1746. He had arrived on the Mont in September 1745; he was detained for a little less than a year and not thirty as some authors have claimed.] <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 160-2</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
